{"key":"processedPost-16529921","value":{"id":16529921,"first":16527708,"last":16529921,"when":1342285694,"utime":"07/14/12 08:08 PM","content":"<blockquote>Quote:<br />How long would you guys say a mono culture on a petrie would last? If it was fully colonized, and stayed contamination free in the fridge.<br /></blockquote><br /><br />It depends on species.&nbsp; However, you should never let a petri dish fully colonize.&nbsp; I've seen mycelium crawl out between the lid and base, colonize through the parafilm or other wrap, and then become contaminated when exposed to air.&nbsp; Use refrigeration to prevent the mycelium from colonizing the last 1/4\" or so of the petri dish agar surface.<br /><br />Also bear in mind, many tropical species hate refrigeration and don't last long.&nbsp; For these species, room temperature(or slightly cooler) storage of slants is preferred.<br />RR","title":"Re: A few agar questions","forum":"Mushroom Cultivation"}}